<br>
I agree. TV should most definetly not be a tool used to help raise our children. As a parent, it is your responsibility to police what your children watch and listen to. If you don't like it, don't let them watch it.  Or, better yet, let them watch it... but watch it with them.  If something is said you don't agree with, tell your child you think that's wrong, and why.  Give them the opportunity to weigh both opinions and make thier own decision.<br>
<br>
What I don't understand is why you seem to think a muppet with a disease is teaching values you don't want your child to have. You want your children to be afraid of sick people? I said it before and I'll say it again. AIDS is a disease, not a lifestyle. This is no different to me then showing a cancer muppet.<br>
<br>
Why is an AIDS puppet so risque? Because it is stigmatized as a &quot;homosexual disease?&quot; I like to think that we, as a society, are enlightened enough to realize that AIDS is non-discriminatory. Homosexuals and heterosexuals alike contract it. Is it taboo because it's largely an STD? The person who gets it (in most cases) brought it upon themselves for having dangerous or unsafe sex? I disagree, but for arguments sake.. I'll play along. If the statement I just made is true, then how about this? I used the example of a cancer puppet. What about people who get lung cancer, or mouth cancer from smoking or chewing? Are we not supposed to feel compassion for them, as they brought the disease upon themselves? Would we want our children showing disdain and fear to one of these unlucky people?<br>
<br>
How about this? It's a proven fact that to educate a child about an issue is far more effective than blanketly telling them &quot;Don't do that.&quot; You don't want your child to get pregnant or get some STD? Teach them about sex, why they should wait to have it, what the repercussions will be, and that if they are going to have sex anyways... make sure it's safe sex. A lot of people are saying that they disagree because Sesame Streets target audience is ages 3-7. You know what that says to me? It says that this will bring up a lot of relevant and honest questions from those kids that the parents don't want to answer. It is never too soon to educate your child about lifes issues they'll undoubtedly come across.  <p><br> <br> <br> <center><img src="http://www.lunaclara.com/fark/LourdesSig.gif"></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubrendariloupegarou.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brendari Loupegarou</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>12 Inch Nervis</span><br>  Posts: 142<br> <font color=#333333>(7/25/02 1:26:40 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.lunaclara.com/fark/newsig.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Liberals strike again</span><hr size=1> Speaking of Mr. Rogers... he talked about the Kennedy assassination on his show. Not directly, mind you, but he dealt with how children might perceive that time of confusion and mourning and I believe helped them get through it.<br>
